The problem asks for the projection of the vector $-2\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{w}$, given the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{w}$.

First, recall the property of linearity for vector projections. Specifically, for any scalar $c$ and vectors $\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w}$, the projection satisfies $\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{w}} (c\mathbf{v}) = c \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{w}} \mathbf{v}$ -> In this case, the scalar $c$ is $-2$. Therefore, we simply multiply the given projection vector $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}$ by the scalar $-2$ -> Performing the scalar multiplication component-wise: $-2 \cdot 1 = -2$, $-2 \cdot 0 = 0$, and $-2 \cdot (-3) = 6$ -> Thus, the resulting vector is $\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}$.

#### \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}

